Here's everything you need to give developers **read-only log access** in Kubernetes using RBAC:

---

## Kubernetes RBAC for Developer Log Access

### 1. ClusterRole — defines what's allowed

```yaml
# developer-log-reader-clusterrole.yaml
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRole
metadata:
  name: developer-log-reader
rules:
  - apiGroups: [""]
    resources: ["pods", "pods/log"]
    verbs: ["get", "list", "watch"]
  - apiGroups: [""]
    resources: ["namespaces"]
    verbs: ["get", "list"]
```

> This grants read access to pods and their logs across the cluster.

---

### 2. Option A — Namespace-scoped (recommended)

Restrict developers to specific namespaces using a **RoleBinding**:

```yaml
# developer-log-rolebinding.yaml
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: developer-log-reader-binding
  namespace: your-namespace        # 👈 change this
subjects:
  - kind: User
    name: developer@example.com    # 👈 or use a Group
    apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: developer-log-reader
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
```

Apply it:
```bash
kubectl apply -f developer-log-reader-clusterrole.yaml
kubectl apply -f developer-log-rolebinding.yaml
```

---

### 3. Option B — Cluster-wide access

If the developer needs logs across **all namespaces**, use a **ClusterRoleBinding** instead:

```yaml
# developer-log-clusterrolebinding.yaml
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: developer-log-reader-global
subjects:
  - kind: User
    name: developer@example.com
    apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: developer-log-reader
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
```

---

### 4. For a Group of developers

Replace `kind: User` with `kind: Group` to apply to many users at once:

```yaml
subjects:
  - kind: Group
    name: developers          # matches group in your identity provider
    apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
```

---

### 5. Verify the access

```bash
# Test as a specific user
kubectl auth can-i get pods/log --namespace=your-namespace --as=developer@example.com

# List what a user can do
kubectl auth can-i --list --namespace=your-namespace --as=developer@example.com
```

---

### What developers can do with this access

```bash
# View logs of a pod
kubectl logs <pod-name> -n your-namespace

# Follow/stream logs
kubectl logs -f <pod-name> -n your-namespace

# Logs from a specific container
kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container-name> -n your-namespace

# Previous container logs (after crash)
kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous -n your-namespace
```

---

**Key decision:** Use **RoleBinding** (namespace-scoped) unless developers genuinely need cross-namespace visibility — principle of least privilege applies. Let me know if you'd like this tailored to a specific auth provider (OIDC, AWS IAM, GKE Workload Identity, etc.).
